# Networking Fundamentals Notes

## Introduction

While learning networking fundamentals, I understood how devices communicate with each other over a network. At first some topics like protocols and ports were confusing, but after practicing and reading examples they became easier to understand.

Networking knowledge is important in cybersecurity because most attacks and communications happen through networks.

---

# IP Address

An IP address is used to identify devices on a network.

Example:
192.168.1.1

I learned that every device connected to a network needs an IP address to communicate with other devices.

There are mainly two types:
- Public IP
- Private IP

---

# TCP and UDP

## TCP
TCP is a reliable communication protocol.

Features:
- Connection-oriented
- Reliable data transfer
- Error checking

Examples:
- HTTP
- HTTPS
- SSH

I understood TCP as a slower but more reliable protocol.

---

## UDP
UDP is faster but less reliable.

Features:
- No connection setup
- Faster communication
- No guaranteed delivery

Examples:
- DNS
- Online games
- Streaming

At first I found it difficult to compare TCP and UDP, but later I understood:
- TCP focuses on reliability
- UDP focuses on speed

---

# DNS

DNS stands for Domain Name System.

It converts domain names into IP addresses.

Example:
google.com → IP address

Without DNS, users would need to remember IP addresses instead of domain names.

---

# Common Ports

Ports help identify services running on a system.

| Port | Service |
|---|---|
| 21 | FTP |
| 22 | SSH |
| 53 | DNS |
| 80 | HTTP |
| 443 | HTTPS |
| 445 | SMB |
| 3389 | RDP |

I learned that attackers often scan ports to discover running services.

---

# Port Scanning

Port scanning is used to identify open ports and services.

Common tool:
Nmap

Example:
nmap target_ip

This was one of the interesting topics because it showed how systems can be enumerated.

---

# Ping Command

The ping command is used to test connectivity between systems.

Example:
ping google.com

I used this command several times to check whether the network connection was working properly.

---

# MAC Address

A MAC address is the physical hardware address of a device.

Example:
00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E

Unlike IP addresses, MAC addresses are tied to hardware.

---

